{
  "What is the momentum of a 3 kg object moving at 8 m/s?": "",
  "48 kg·m/s": "",
  "24 kg·m/s": "",
  "2.67 kg·m/s": "",
  "11 kg·m/s": "",
  "Momentum p = mv = 3(8) = 24 kg·m/s.": "",
  "A 0.5 kg ball moving at 10 m/s is stopped in 0.1 s. What is the average force on the ball?": "",
  "50 N": "",
  "5 N": "",
  "0.5 N": "",
  "500 N": "",
  "Impulse = Δp = 0.5(10) = 5 kg·m/s. F = Δp/Δt = 5/0.1 = 50 N.": "",
  "A constant force of 20 N acts on an object for 3 seconds. What is the impulse delivered?": "",
  "60 N·s": "",
  "6.67 N·s": "",
  "23 N·s": "",
  "120 N·s": "",
  "Impulse J = FΔt = 20(3) = 60 N·s.": "",
  "Two objects with momenta of 15 kg·m/s east and 20 kg·m/s west collide and stick together. What is the total momentum after the collision?": "",
  "35 kg·m/s east": "",
  "0 kg·m/s": "",
  "5 kg·m/s west": "",
  "5 kg·m/s east": "",
  "Total momentum is conserved: 15 + (-20) = -5 kg·m/s, which is 5 kg·m/s west.": "",
  "A 2 kg cart moving at 6 m/s collides with a stationary 4 kg cart and they stick together. What is their final velocity?": "",
  "1 m/s": "",
  "3 m/s": "",
  "6 m/s": "",
  "2 m/s": "",
  "Conservation of momentum: m₁v₁ = (m₁ + m₂)v_f. 2(6) = (2+4)v_f, v_f = 12/6 = 2 m/s.": "",
  "A force F(t) = 12t (in Newtons) acts on a 4 kg object at rest for 3 seconds. What is the final momentum?": "",
  "36 kg·m/s": "",
  "108 kg·m/s": "",
  "54 kg·m/s": "",
  "18 kg·m/s": "",
  "Impulse = integral of F dt from 0 to 3 = integral of 12t dt = 6t² from 0 to 3 = 6(9) = 54 N·s = 54 kg·m/s.": "",
  "A 0.15 kg baseball moving at 40 m/s is hit by a bat and returns at 50 m/s. What is the magnitude of the change in momentum?": "",
  "1.5 kg·m/s": "",
  "6.75 kg·m/s": "",
  "9 kg·m/s": "",
  "13.5 kg·m/s": "",
  "|Δp| = m|v_f - v_i| = 0.15|(-50) - 40| = 0.15(90) = 13.5 kg·m/s.": "",
  "In a perfectly inelastic collision, which quantity is always conserved?": "",
  "Kinetic energy": "",
  "Momentum": "",
  "Speed": "",
  "Velocity": "",
  "Momentum is always conserved in collisions (when no external forces act). Kinetic energy is NOT conserved in perfectly inelastic collisions.": "",
  "A 5 kg object at rest explodes into two pieces: one piece (2 kg) moves at 10 m/s to the right. What is the velocity of the other piece?": "",
  "4 m/s to the left": "",
  "6.67 m/s to the right": "",
  "10 m/s to the left": "",
  "6.67 m/s to the left": "",
  "Initial momentum = 0. So 2(10) + 3(v) = 0, v = -20/3 ≈ -6.67 m/s (to the left).": "",
  "A rubber ball (0.2 kg) bounces off a wall, hitting at 5 m/s and rebounding at 5 m/s. What impulse does the wall exert?": "",
  "0.5 N·s": "",
  "0 N·s": "",
  "1 N·s": "",
  "2 N·s": "",
  "J = Δp = m(v_f - v_i) = 0.2(5 - (-5)) = 0.2(10) = 2 N·s away from the wall.": "",
  "What is momentum?": "",
  "The rate of change of velocity": "",
  "The energy of motion": "",
  "The product of an object's mass and velocity: p = mv, a vector quantity": "",
  "The force required to stop an object": "",
  "Momentum is defined as p = mv, a vector quantity with the same direction as velocity, measured in kg·m/s.": "",
  "What is the impulse-momentum theorem?": "",
  "The work done equals the change in kinetic energy": "",
  "Momentum is always conserved in any interaction": "",
  "The impulse on an object equals the change in its momentum: J = integral of F dt = Δp": "",
  "Force equals mass times acceleration": "",
  "The impulse-momentum theorem states J = integral of F dt = Δp, connecting the time integral of force to the change in momentum.": "",
  "What does 'conservation of momentum' mean?": "",
  "The momentum of each object in a system stays the same": "",
  "In a closed system with no external forces, the total momentum remains constant": "",
  "Momentum is a scalar that is always positive": "",
  "Momentum increases when a force is applied": "",
  "Conservation of momentum states that when no net external force acts on a system, the total momentum (vector sum) remains constant through all interactions.": "",
  "What is impulse?": "",
  "The product of force and distance, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "The kinetic energy of an object, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "The rate of change of momentum in most scenarios involving force factors": "",
  "The product of force and the time interval over which it acts: J = F·Δt (or J = integral of F dt for variable force)": "",
  "Impulse is the integral of force over time (J = integral of F dt). For constant force, J = FΔt. It equals the change in momentum and is measured in N·s.": "",
  "What is a perfectly inelastic collision?": "",
  "A collision where kinetic energy is conserved": "",
  "A collision where the objects stick together and maximum kinetic energy is lost": "",
  "A collision between identical objects": "",
  "A collision where momentum is not conserved": "",
  "In a perfectly inelastic collision, objects stick together after impact. Momentum is conserved but the maximum amount of kinetic energy is converted to other forms.": "",
  "What is an elastic collision?": "",
  "A collision where objects stick together": "",
  "A collision involving springs": "",
  "Any collision between bouncing objects": "",
  "A collision where both momentum and kinetic energy are conserved": "",
  "In an elastic collision, both total momentum and total kinetic energy are conserved. Atomic and molecular collisions are often approximately elastic.": "",
  "What is the center-of-mass frame?": "",
  "A frame where all objects are at rest": "",
  "A frame where the center of mass is at the origin": "",
  "The laboratory frame of reference": "",
  "A reference frame moving with the velocity of the center of mass, where total momentum is zero": "",
  "The center-of-mass frame moves with v_cm, so the total momentum in this frame is zero. This simplifies collision analysis considerably.": "",
  "What does the term 'coefficient of restitution' mean?": "",
  "The spring constant of the collision surface": "",
  "The ratio of the relative speed of separation to the relative speed of approach in a collision: e = |v₂f - v₁f|/|v₁i - v₂i|": "",
  "The fraction of momentum lost in a collision": "",
  "The ratio of final to initial kinetic energy": "",
  "The coefficient of restitution e ranges from 0 (perfectly inelastic) to 1 (perfectly elastic), measuring how 'bouncy' a collision is.": "",
  "What is the relationship between force and momentum expressed by Newton's second law?": "",
  "Momentum equals force times distance": "",
  "F = mΔv regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "F = mv, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "F_net = dp/dt, the net force equals the time derivative of momentum": "",
  "Newton's second law in its most general form states F_net = dp/dt. When mass is constant, this reduces to F = ma.": "",
  "What does 'internal force' mean in the context of momentum conservation?": "",
  "The normal force on an object": "",
  "A force that is always conservative": "",
  "A force that acts from outside the system": "",
  "A force between objects within the defined system, which cannot change the total momentum of the system": "",
  "Internal forces act between objects within the system. By Newton's third law, they come in equal and opposite pairs and cannot change the system's total momentum.": "",
  "A 2000 kg car traveling east at 20 m/s collides with a 3000 kg truck traveling north at 10 m/s. They lock bumpers. What is the speed and direction of the wreckage?": "",
  "14 m/s at 45° north of east": "",
  "6 m/s due northeast": "",
  "12 m/s at 53° north of east": "",
  "10 m/s at 37° north of east": "",
  "p_east = 2000(20) = 40,000 kg·m/s. p_north = 3000(10) = 30,000 kg·m/s. Total mass = 5000 kg. v_east = 8, v_north = 6. Speed = sqrt(64+36) = 10 m/s. θ = arctan(6/8) = 37° north of east.": "",
  "A bullet (0.01 kg) traveling at 400 m/s embeds in a 2 kg block on a frictionless surface. The block then slides up a ramp. What maximum height does it reach? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "0.02 m": "",
  "0.20 m": "",
  "2.0 m": "",
  "0.04 m": "",
  "After collision: v = 0.01(400)/(0.01+2) = 4/2.01 ≈ 1.99 m/s. Height: h = v²/(2g) = (1.99)²/20 ≈ 0.20 m.": "",
  "A spacecraft (1000 kg) ejects 50 kg of exhaust at 200 m/s relative to the spacecraft. If the spacecraft was initially at rest, what is its velocity after the ejection?": "",
  "20 m/s": "",
  "10 m/s": "",
  "10.5 m/s": "",
  "100 m/s": "",
  "Conservation of momentum: 0 = 950v - 50(200 - v). 0 = 950v - 10000 + 50v = 1000v - 10000. v = 10 m/s. With relative velocity: 0 = (1000-50)v_s + 50(v_s - 200), so 1000v_s = 10000, v_s = 10 m/s. More precisely ≈ 10.5 m/s accounting for the relative velocity.": "",
  "A tennis ball (0.06 kg) hits a racket at 30 m/s. The racket exerts a force modeled as F(t) = 600sin(πt/0.01) N for 0 ≤ t ≤ 0.01 s. What is the ball's velocity after the hit?": "",
  "Approximately 20 m/s in the original direction": "",
  "Approximately 50 m/s in the return direction": "",
  "Approximately 33.5 m/s in the return direction": "",
  "Approximately 33.7 m/s in the return direction": "",
  "J = integral of 600sin(πt/0.01) dt from 0 to 0.01 = 600[-0.01/π cos(πt/0.01)] from 0 to 0.01 = (6/π)(1+1) = 12/π ≈ 3.82 N·s. Δp = J, so 0.06v_f - 0.06(-30) = 3.82. v_f = (3.82 - 1.8)/0.06 ≈ 33.7 m/s.": "",
